portunity for something new.=C2=A0
Second, the technological infrastructure on which oncyber is building is re=
ady.=C2=A0
Almost exactly a year ago, Pace Capital=E2=80=99s Chris Paik went on Invest=
 Like the Best [ https://substack.com/redirect/0e0aeaf2-309e-4dd2-8c8a-c2a0=
17966dd9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ], right around the time that Apple announced the Vision Pro. Responding t=
o Patrick O=E2=80=99Shaughnessy=E2=80=99s question about the history of hum=
anity as a data and storage transfer problem, he said:=C2=A0
One thing that I think is underexplored is the impact of data transfer spee=
ds as actual why now reasons for companies existing. Let's look at mobile s=
ocial networks and the order that they were founded in; Twitter 2006, Insta=
gram 2010, Snapchat 2011, maybe most recently TikTok named Musical.ly in 20=
14.
It could not have happened in any other order because of the minimum packet=
 size of the content on that platform.=C2=A0
Over the past five years, data transfer speeds on fixed broadband have more=
 than doubled, from 45.9 Mbps in 2018 to 110.4 Mbps in 2023, according to C=
isco=E2=80=99s 2023 Annual Report [ https://substack.com/redirect/19aa10d1-=
bbb9-4987-8fd7-afcc6490ea0f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. According to the same report, the average mobile spe=
ed more than tripled over the same period, from 13.2 Mbps to 43.9 Mbps, and=
 the average 5G speed is 13 times higher: 575 Mbps in 2023.=C2=A0
From a speed perspective, the bandwidth is there to support multiplayer, in=
teractive, 3D experiences at scale.=C2=A0
There are other, more powerful and oncyber-specific forces at play, too.=C2=
=A0
Three years ago, fully flexible creation would have been limited to people =
who knew how to code, and who, even still, would have had to learn a new sc=
ripting language. In that situation, no-code worldbuilders like Roblox and =
Minecraft made more sense =E2=80=93 anyone, even kids, could build there, e=
ven if the tools limited what they could build.=C2=A0
Now, with AI and oncyber=E2=80=99s framework, anyone can translate their im=
agination into code into a fully-functioning, immersive website. That means=
 that people can build practically anything, like the internet as opposed t=
o a specific piece of software.=C2=A0
Three years ago, oncyber could have built in crypto rails, but transactions=
 would have been slow and expensive, and people would have needed to figure=
 out how to set up their own wallets.=C2=A0
Now, with stablecoins and account abstraction, oncyber can provide fast, re=
liable transactions to anyone, whether they=E2=80=99ve used crypto before o=
r not, natively. Not because it=E2=80=99s crypto, but because it=E2=80=99s =
smoother, cheaper, and more flexible.=C2=A0
That means that creators have more flexibility to play with new business mo=
dels, which is important if we=E2=80=99re going to escape the optimization-=
induced enshittification. Both Perez and Christensen argue that new technol=
ogical revolutions and disruptive innovations, respectively, require new bu=
siness models.=C2=A0
There are other external forces that oncyber is riding, like the rise of we=
b technologies like WebGL and WebXR that make web-based 3D experiences easi=
er to build and render on laptops and in headsets. The technological why no=
w makes sense.=C2=A0
But whether oncyber succeeds or fails will depend on what people can build =
with it.=C2=A0
Can It Do X?=20
The most expressive tools make you ask, =E2=80=9CWait, can it do X?=E2=80=
=9D, and answer =E2=80=9CYes.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s the experience I had when Rayan gave me the demo, and it=E2=
=80=99s when I realized that this could be much more than a web-based gamin=
g platform, that it could power whatever comes next for the internet.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWait, can multiple people participate at the same time?=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CYes. Multiplayer comes built-in. People can play with and talk to =
each other, or AI NPCs.=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=9CWait, can you create any environment you want?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CYes. You start with a blank slate or a template, and you can chang=
e everything.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWait, can I add images, links, videos?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CYes. You can add any content you want, and put it wherever you wan=
t.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
As I asked questions and Rayan showed me the answers, I started to picture =
websites that are as easy to build as today=E2=80=99s 2D static websites, m=
aybe easier, but that are packed with more functionality, interactivity, an=
d fun.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWait, could I make an interactive website that=E2=80=99s not a gam=
e, like Yamauchi No. 10=E2=80=99s?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CYes. I=E2=80=99ll whip it up for you this weekend.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Yamauchi No. 10 is the Nintendo Family Office. Its website [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/1fdc77fa-d0bb-423b-ba8d-b8f65f9f3859?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is my favorite.=C2=A0
I like it because it=E2=80=99s whimsical, because it=E2=80=99s fun, and mos=
t of all because it=E2=80=99s different. And not just different, but differ=
ent in a way that=E2=80=99s unique to Yamauchi No. 10. Nintendo is a gaming=
 company, and the website of the family office that gaming funded reflects =
that heritage.=C2=A0
I forgot when I started writing this piece, but I actually included it in t=
hat Interfaces [ https://substack.com/redirect/0b57097b-ab89-4310-b0be-a462=
cff25c26?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] essay in 2021. I wrote: =E2=80=9CIf you haven=E2=80=99t seen the Yamuchi=
 No. 10 Family Office website [ https://substack.com/redirect/1fdc77fa-d0bb=
-423b-ba8d-b8f65f9f3859?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], check it out for a glimpse of the future.=E2=80=9D
The future is here. In just a couple hours, while preparing for the launch =
of v2, Rayan was able to whip up Not Boring=E2=80=99s version of Yamauchi N=
o. 10.=20
You can play with it here [ https://substack.com/redirect/3459c808-2334-49d=
c-8c60-8e6759a3c469?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ].
If you want to play Snake right on top of the words, just hit =E2=80=9CS=E2=
=80=9D.
Is it as beautiful and detailed as Yamauchi No. 10=E2=80=99s? No. Is it pre=
tty fucking cool, and does it have Snake built right in? Yes. And will it c=
ontinue to get better? For sure.
In the next few weeks, oncyber will hand over the reins and I=E2=80=99ll be=
 able to tweak this site to my preferences =E2=80=93 color schemes, billboa=
rds with my latest essays, a portfolio page. I haven=E2=80=99t made a websi=
te for Not Boring or Not Boring Capital beyond Substack because I haven=E2=
=80=99t wanted to pay an agency $50k to develop something that looked prett=
y much like everyone else=E2=80=99s websites, but I=E2=80=99m really excite=
d to make something unique and weird with their tools.=C2=A0
The magical thing is not that Rayan could make me my own Yamauchi, as cool =
as that is, but that seemingly whatever I dreamed up and asked for, the ans=
wer would be =E2=80=9CYes.=E2=80=9D An internet bounded by my creativity.=
=C2=A0
What=E2=80=99s Next on the Internet
As I wrote in Interfaces [ https://substack.com/redirect/0b57097b-ab89-4310=
-b0be-a462cff25c26?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9Cfar more creative and talented people are going to c=
ome up with ideas that blow everything I wrote out of the water, and other =
people are going to come in and build even wilder experiences on top of tho=
se ideas.=E2=80=9D
These experiences are not going to be SEO optimized. Instead of being passi=
vely discovered via search, they=E2=80=99ll have to be so good that people =
seek them out. They=E2=80=99ll spread through word of mouth. People will on=
e-up each other, create weirder, more unique, and more magical experiences.=
 If they optimize for anything, it will be creativity.=C2=A0
Instead of a generic ecommerce site, brands could create virtual stores whe=
re live or AI salespeople can interact with customers in real-time, and whe=
re customers can checkout in a click, maybe even using crypto they=E2=80=99=
ve won playing a game. As entrepreneurs race to build realistic avatars of =
you that can try on clothes for fit, oncyber can incorporate them as compon=
ents.=C2=A0
Anyone who wants to create virtual hangout spaces for their friends =E2=80=
=93 an immersive turntable.fm, a drive-in movie theater, or just a more fun=
 chat room =E2=80=93 can build it in a few hours.=C2=A0
Kids can program their own 3D versions of Snake the way me and all of my fr=
iends programmed Snake into our TI-83 calculators back in the day. On our c=
all, I asked Rayan to make Snake, and he did it in like 10 minutes, right b=
efore my eyes, and then built it into my Yamauchi site.=C2=A0
Again, my ideas are going to be so much more limited than the collective ge=
nius of everyone on the internet once they get their hands on these tools. =
I=E2=80=99m sure you=E2=80=99re thinking of better ones as you read this.=
=C2=A0
And when Apple inevitably comes out with a cheaper, lighter version of the =
VisionPro, or as Zuck=E2=80=99s vision of bringing realistic worlds to sung=
lasses within the decade comes to pass, the virtual world will already be r=
ichly populated with 3D experiences built for all 5 billion of the internet=
=E2=80=99s users. Something like oncyber may even speed up the adoption of =
VR/AR by solving the developer cold start problem on those platforms.=C2=A0
When something feels like it=E2=80=99s broken beyond repair, that=E2=80=99s=
 usually a pretty good sign that the next thing is right around the corner.=
 The current internet feels broken. It=E2=80=99s time for the next version.=
 Worlds instead of websites.=C2=A0
The version you=E2=80=99ll play with today will look like a toy (literally,=
 like a game).=C2=A0
The team has a lot of work left to do to create a product with which anyone=
, technical and non-technical alike can build. I=E2=80=99m sure there will =
be bugginess. And oncyber won=E2=80=99t be right for every company with a w=
ebsite, to start. It will undershoot on some basic needs for more sophistic=
ated creators.=C2=A0
But for other creators, oncyber will offer tools they can=E2=80=99t find an=
ywhere else, and let them create things they couldn=E2=80=99t anywhere else=
=2E It=E2=80=99s a game engine that can make websites.=C2=A0
And it will improve. Creators will build new templates and components, and =
get rewarded for doing so. As crypto and AI improve, oncyber will be able t=
o surf their progress. People will mix and remix, one-up each other in a po=
sitive sum race.=C2=A0
In fact, whether oncyber is the platform that births this next phase of the=
 internet will come down to the engagement of early creators, their desire =
to mix, remix, build new building blocks, and compose them in new ways.=C2=
=A0
If they do, the internet could get really fun, really quickly. In a few yea=
rs, we might look back on the 2D, static, slop-filled internet as an unbeli=
evably archaic relic.=C2=A0
I could, of course, be wrong about all of this. Maybe the internet will con=
tinue its slide into slop. Maybe AI will just mean super-SEO and coders usi=
ng AI to build more, much more, much faster, of the same old stuff. Maybe 2=
D and static is the ultimate form for our digital experiences. Maybe the in=
ternet is impervious to the death and rebirth that comes for all industries=
=2E=C2=A0
Only one way to find out.=C2=A0
Go play with oncyber and build a new internet.=C2=A0
Make the internet fun again.=C2=A0
